<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level DELETE ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_manager` UNCONDITIONAL delete access
    on records of the `x_casemgmt_case` custom table inside the scoped
    application `x_casemgmt`. This is the DELETE companion to the case_manager
    create / read / write ACLs (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml,
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_manager.xml, ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_manager.xml)
    and together those four files materialize the AAP Section 0.5.6 row:
    "x_casemgmt_case_manager : Create=Yes, Read=All, Write=All, Delete=Yes."

    Of the four CRUD operations, DELETE is the most-restricted on the case
    table: only the case_manager role gets it. There is intentionally NO
    sibling x_casemgmt_case_delete_agent.xml file and NO sibling
    x_casemgmt_case_delete_viewer.xml file — those two roles are denied delete
    by the ABSENCE of a granting ACL (ServiceNow record-level ACLs are
    deny-by-default; a role with no granting ACL for an operation cannot
    perform that operation). The deny is therefore enforced structurally —
    no scripted "deny" rule is required, and no inverse condition is encoded.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) — case_manager row (verbatim from AAP):
            | Role                    | Create | Read | Write | Delete |
            | x_casemgmt_case_manager  |  Yes   | All  |  All  |  Yes   |
        This file authors the single "Delete = Yes" cell. The "Yes" Create
        cell is authored by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml; the
        "All" Read cell by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_manager.xml; the "All"
        Write cell by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_manager.xml. Each row of the
        ACL matrix maps to exactly one or zero ACL XML files — this per-cell
        granularity is what lets the Update Set add or remove role privileges
        independently without entangling roles or operations.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) — all-roles delete coverage:
            - case_manager: Delete=Yes -> THIS FILE
            - case_agent:   Delete=No  -> deliberate absence of any
                                          x_casemgmt_case_delete_agent.xml
            - case_viewer:  Delete=No  -> deliberate absence of any
                                          x_casemgmt_case_delete_viewer.xml
        Together these three facts implement the user prompt's contract that
        only managers — who are responsible for the full case lifecycle and
        records-management oversight — may destroy case records. Agents (who
        merely process assigned cases) and viewers (audit / compliance /
        supervisor tier with read-only access) cannot delete. This protects
        historical data integrity for the POC's reporting surfaces (the
        Manager View dashboard's "average time to close" and "cases opened in
        last 30 days" widgets per AAP Section 0.4.4 depend on closed cases
        remaining queryable; agent-driven deletion would silently corrupt
        those metrics).
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 — ACLs):
            "Role-based access enforced — case_viewer cannot write; case_agent
             cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has full access."
        The clause "case_manager has full access" requires that the manager
        role be able to perform every CRUD operation on the case table, of
        which delete is the fourth and most-elevated. This ACL satisfies that
        clause for the delete operation; the parallel clauses about
        case_viewer (no write) and case_agent (no unassigned-case access) are
        unaffected by this ACL and are enforced by separate sibling ACL files
        (case_viewer never appears in any write/create/delete ACL; case_agent
        delete is enforced by absence as noted above).
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications — Scoped role-based access
        control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and field-level
        ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL expressions,
        replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig map." This ACL
        is the table-level DELETE binding for the highest-tier scoped role
        and is one of the declarative facts the platform's sys_security_acl
        evaluator consumes when authorizing a row deletion at runtime.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation — Access-control
        transformation): "ApplicationRolesConfig + RolesPrivilegesService +
        URL-based privilege metadata -> scoped roles + ACLs." In ArkCase the
        equivalent of THIS file would have been a single entry in the
        rolesToPrivileges map binding the manager-equivalent role to a
        privilege identifier such as `acm-case-delete` or `acm-case-remove`,
        evaluated at HTTP request time by AcmPluginUrlPrivilege against the
        DELETE verb on the casefile REST endpoint. The ServiceNow target
        replaces both the map binding and the URL-privilege evaluator with
        this single declarative ACL record.

    Why advanced=false (no scripted condition for delete):
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6, the case_manager role's privileges are
      unconditional ("All", "Full access") — there is no "Assigned only" or
      other row-level filter. Therefore:
        - <advanced>false</advanced>      — no scripted condition
        - <condition/>                    — empty encoded query (no row filter)
        - <script/>                       — empty server-side script
      With no condition and no script, the ACL evaluates to "permit" for any
      caller who carries the x_casemgmt_case_manager role. This is the
      correct semantic for the AAP's "manager has full delete" requirement.
      Setting advanced=true with an empty script would be functionally
      equivalent but stylistically incorrect — the ServiceNow convention is
      to reserve advanced=true for ACLs that actually carry a scripted body.

    Why DELETE is granted to manager only (design rationale):
      - Records-management discipline: case records are the durable artifact
        of every interaction the organization has with a requester. Deletion
        is irreversible and removes audit trail. Agents process cases;
        viewers observe cases; only managers — who own the lifecycle from
        intake to closure — have authority to remove records.
      - Reporting integrity: the Manager View dashboard
        (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml) computes
        "Average time to close" and "Cases opened in last 30 days" by
        aggregating across the entire case table. Allowing agents to delete
        would let any one agent silently distort organization-wide KPIs.
      - Portal anonymity contract: the external Experience Portal
        (../portal/sp_portal_x_casemgmt_case_portal.xml) accepts anonymous
        case submissions through ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml.
        Anonymous callers and unauthenticated portal users have NO scoped
        role at all and therefore — by the same deny-by-default principle —
        have NO delete capability via this ACL. The portal contract is
        preserved automatically.
      - State-machine cleanup: when a case enters the terminal `Closed`
        state, the before-update business rule
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml prohibits
        further updates to that record. Deletion is a separate operation
        from update and is governed by THIS ACL — only managers can purge
        a closed case from the system. Agents who attempt to delete will
        receive ServiceNow's standard "Operation against file 'x_casemgmt_case'
        was aborted by Business Rule" deny response from the platform.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section 0.3.2;
    no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/services/
        users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration map
        (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by the property
        `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that model, a "manager-equivalent"
        role (e.g., ROLE_CASE_MANAGER) would have been associated with a
        delete privilege identifier such as `acm-case-delete`. The ServiceNow
        target replaces this map-based privilege association with declarative,
        scoped record-level ACLs — this XML record is the direct equivalent
        of one cell in the map: the (case_manager, DELETE) pairing.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        `removeRolesPrivileges(...)`). All of this Java service surface is
        replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted privilege resolver is needed.
        Notably, ArkCase's `userDao.deleteAcmRole(roleName)` call removed an
        entire role definition — that operation has no analog in this file
        because role definitions in ServiceNow are themselves managed by the
        ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_*.xml records, not by ACLs. THIS
        ACL governs the deletion of CASE RECORDS, not the deletion of the
        role itself.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into the
        x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package source = x_casemgmt).
        No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field references the
        scoped table x_casemgmt_case (not the OOB `task` table or any other
        global table), and <roles> references the scoped role
        x_casemgmt_case_manager. There are zero global writes from this file.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name /
        source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The <sys_id> below
        is THIS record's own deterministic primary key (MD5 of
        "x_casemgmt_case.delete.case_manager", a stable canonical identifier
        for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to any other record.
        Computing the sys_id deterministically guarantees the ACL is
        re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs and round-trip Update Set
        previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case` with NO
        dot. ServiceNow's delete operation has no concept of "delete this
        specific column" — field-level ACLs apply only to read/write/none.
        The <type>record</type> field below confirms this is a row-level
        (table-level) ACL, not a UI/REST/SOAP-flavored ACL. The two
        field-level ACL files in this folder
        (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml) restrict who
        can WRITE those specific columns; they have no bearing on row
        deletion, which is governed exclusively by this file.
      - Operation = delete: corresponds exactly to the "Delete = Yes" cell
        in the AAP matrix for the case_manager role.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows the
        platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required so
        platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or remove scoped
        seed data (per AAP Section 0.7.4 the seed_demo_data.js script can
        re-seed a fresh PDI; if a prior partial run left stale demo cases,
        the admin user — who does NOT need the scoped case_manager role —
        must still be able to clean up). It does NOT widen case_manager
        privileges — non-admin managers see exactly what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = false: see "Why advanced=false" rationale above. The
        platform skips the empty <script/> body entirely.
      - condition (empty): the <condition/> encoded-query field is empty;
        no row-level filter applies to manager deletes (manager has "full"
        access, not "Assigned only").
      - script (empty): the <script/> field is empty; the platform skips
        it because advanced=false.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record — resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (resolves <name>x_casemgmt_case</name>
          by table name lookup at apply time)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles> by role name lookup at
          apply time)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml
          (the demo manager's delete access during round-trip verification
          depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - any cleanup or re-seed activity in ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
          that may delete prior demo cases; while seed_demo_data.js itself
          runs as admin and bypasses this ACL via admin_overrides, post-seed
          smoke tests against the demo dataset depend on this ACL being
          applied so a logged-in demo manager can validate end-to-end
          delete capability.
      The deny-by-default sibling pairs that this file works with:
        - x_casemgmt_case_delete_agent.xml  (DOES NOT EXIST — by design)
        - x_casemgmt_case_delete_viewer.xml (DOES NOT EXIST — by design)
      Adding either of those files would VIOLATE the AAP Section 0.5.6
      matrix and MUST NOT be done by any future agent.

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used verbatim per AAP convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"). ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
    scope id is concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped application. The deterministic sys_id below is computed against the
    `casemgmt` literal and remains stable across re-imports onto fresh PDIs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>false</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Table-level ACL: x_casemgmt_case_manager can delete x_casemgmt_case records. case_agent and case_viewer have no delete privilege (deny-by-default).</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case</name>
        <operation>delete</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles>
        <script/>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>704775b2c264cae37cdc984ee173d307</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_case</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_delete_manager</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
